If you prefer handling the email sending directly from JavaScript without relying on Formspree or similar services, you can use SMTPJS. However, this method involves exposing your SMTP credentials in client-side code, which poses significant security risks. I strongly recommend using Formspree or similar services instead.

If you still want to proceed with SMTPJS, here's how:

a. Using SMTPJS
Sign Up for an Email Service: You'll need SMTP server details. Services like Gmail, SendGrid, or Mailgun can be used. Be aware of their security and rate limits.

Include SMTPJS in Your HTML:

Add the SMTPJS script to your HTML <head>:

html
Copy code
<!--<script src="https://smtpjs.com/v3/smtp.js"></script>
Modify Your Form and JavaScript:

html
Copy code
<form id="projectForm">
  <!-- form fields -->
 <!-- <input type="submit" value="Send">
</form>

<script>
  const form = document.getElementById('projectForm');

  form.addEventListener('submit', function (event) {
    event.preventDefault(); // Prevent the default form submission

    const name = document.getElementById("name").value;
    const email = document.getElementById("email").value;
    const phone = document.getElementById("phone").value;
    const summary = document.getElementById("summary").value;

    Email.send({
      SecureToken: "YOUR_SECURE_TOKEN",
      To: 'deckercasey003@gmail.com',
      From: email,
      Subject: "New Project Submission from " + name,
      Body: `
        Name: ${name}<br>
        Email: ${email}<br>
        Phone: ${phone}<br><br>
        Project Summary:<br>
        ${summary}
      `
    }).then(
      message => {
        if (message === 'OK') {
          alert('Email successfully sent!');
          form.reset();
        } else {
          alert('Failed to send email.');
        }
      }
    );
  });
</script>
Obtain a Secure Token:

Visit SMTPJS.com and follow the instructions to generate a SecureToken. This token allows you to send emails without exposing your SMTP credentials.

Important: Never expose your actual SMTP username and password in client-side code. Using a SecureToken provided by SMTPJS is a safer approach.

Security Considerations:

Even with SecureToken, exposing any email sending mechanism on the client-side can lead to potential misuse or spam. It's crucial to implement additional security measures, such as CAPTCHA or rate limiting, to protect your form from abuse.
Given these risks, using Formspree or a similar service remains the recommended approach.

6. Final Recommendations
Use Formspree: It's secure, easy to set up, and doesn't require you to manage backend code or expose sensitive credentials.

Deploying Your Site: When you're ready to make your site live, ensure that your domain is correctly configured with Formspree and that you've confirmed your email address.

Testing: Always test your form after setup to ensure that emails are being sent and received as expected.

7. Additional Tips
Styling Success and Error Messages: Instead of using alert(), you can display success or error messages within your HTML for a better user experience.

Form Validation: While HTML5 provides basic validation (e.g., required attributes), consider adding additional client-side validation using JavaScript for enhanced user feedback.

Accessibility: Ensure your form is accessible by using proper labels and ARIA attributes where necessary.

Example: Enhanced Form with In-Page Messages
Here's how you can enhance the form to display messages within the page instead of using alert():

html
Copy code
<!-- Add this div below the form to display messages -->
<!--<div id="form-messages"></div>

<form id="projectForm" action="https://formspree.io/f/your-form-id" method="POST">
  <!-- form fields -->
<!--  <input type="submit" value="Send">
</form>

<script>
  const form = document.getElementById('projectForm');
  const formMessages = document.getElementById('form-messages');

  form.addEventListener('submit', function (event) {
    event.preventDefault(); // Prevent the default form submission

    const formData = new FormData(form);

    fetch(form.action, {
      method: 'POST',
      body: formData,
      headers: {
        'Accept': 'application/json'
      }
    })
      .then(response => {
        if (response.ok) {
          formMessages.innerHTML = '<p class="success">Email successfully sent!</p>';
          form.reset();
        } else {
          response.json().then(data => {
            if (Object.hasOwn(data, 'errors')) {
              formMessages.innerHTML = `<p class="error">${data["errors"].map(error => error["message"]).join(", ")}</p>`;
            } else {
              formMessages.innerHTML = '<p class="error">Oops! There was a problem submitting your form.</p>';
            }
          });
        }
      })
      .catch(error => {
        formMessages.innerHTML = '<p class="error">Oops! There was a problem submitting your form.</p>';
      });
  });
</script>

<style>
  /* Add some basic styling for messages */
  #form-messages p {
    padding: 10px;
    border-radius: 5px;
  }

  .success {
    background-color: #d4edda;
    color: #155724;
  }

  .error {
    background-color: #f8d7da;
    color: #721c24;
  }
</style> -->